{
  "answer": "The opening matla (couplet) of Ghalib's famous ghazal states that there are *a thousand wishes, each [one] capable of making [my] spirit cease* (i.e., each desire is so overwhelmingly intense that it could take the poet's life, as \"dam nikle\" literally evokes breath failing or expiring).[^1] The second line reflects paradoxically on how *so many of [the poet's] dreams came true, yet brought so little peace* (or \"still seemed few\"), underscoring the insatiability of human longing despite partial fulfillment.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-fcc8ca](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-fcc8ca).",
